fields.product_description: The iPhone 13 Pro is a premium smartphone from Apple, known for its powerful performance, advanced camera capabilities, and sleek design.

The Galaxy M20 is offered in 3GB RAM and 32GB storage variant in Nepal. It comes with a 6.3-inch display with FULL HD+ resolution and a tiny notch on top. The company has included a dragontrail glass for protection against drops and scratches.
iPhone 11 the direct successor to the iPhone XR, is a 6.1-inch LCD display which they call Liquid Retina of resolution 1,792828 pixels, and 326 PPI.

The iPhone 14 retains the same design as its predecessor. That means a big notch on the front and camera lenses aligned diagonally on the back. The entire body is made of aerospace-grade aluminum and is dust and water resistant to IP68 standards.
Lets now get into the Apple Watch Series 6. Expectations were quite big on this one as initial rumors and leaks hinted at a substantial upgrade for the first time in years.

fields.title: The Future of Technology: A Glimpse into Tomorrow
fields.author: Aashish Basnet
fields.content:
In the ever-evolving landscape of technology, we find ourselves standing on the cusp of an exciting future. The digital revolution, fueled by advancements in artificial intelligence (AI), blockchain, and the Internet of Things (IoT), is reshaping industries and everyday life. In this post, we explore the transformative technologies that will define the coming years.

Artificial Intelligence: The Brain Behind Innovation

Artificial Intelligence (AI) has long been a subject of fascination, and its potential is now being realized in numerous fields. From healthcare to finance, AI is enhancing decision-making, automating tasks, and even predicting outcomes with remarkable precision. In the near future, AI's role will only expand, integrating seamlessly into our lives, whether it's through smarter personal assistants, self-driving cars, or more sophisticated virtual healthcare consultations.

One of the most significant areas where AI is making waves is in machine learning. With the ability to analyze vast datasets and learn from patterns, machine learning enables AI systems to become more intelligent over time, adapting to new information and making better predictions. This is evident in applications like recommendation systems on platforms such as Netflix and Spotify, which continually improve the user experience.

Blockchain: Beyond Cryptocurrency

Blockchain technology, initially known for its association with cryptocurrency like Bitcoin, is now finding applications across various sectors. At its core, blockchain is a decentralized and secure method of recording transactions or data exchanges. Its potential goes far beyond digital currency.

For example, in the supply chain industry, blockchain can provide transparent tracking of goods, reducing fraud and increasing efficiency. In finance, it could revolutionize how transactions are conducted by eliminating the need for intermediaries like banks. Additionally, blockchain could pave the way for secure voting systems, ensuring data integrity and preventing election fraud.

As more industries adopt blockchain, it’s clear that this technology will have a profound impact on the global economy and society.

The Internet of Things (IoT): Connecting the World

The Internet of Things (IoT) refers to the interconnected network of devices that communicate with each other via the internet. From smart home appliances to wearable devices, IoT is already part of our daily lives, but its potential is far from realized. By 2025, it is predicted that there will be over 75 billion IoT devices worldwide.

In smart homes, IoT allows for the automation of everyday tasks like adjusting the thermostat, controlling lights, or monitoring security systems. In industries such as healthcare, IoT enables remote monitoring of patients’ vital signs, allowing for proactive care. In agriculture, IoT devices can monitor soil conditions, helping farmers optimize water usage and crop yield.

The widespread adoption of IoT is making the world more connected, efficient, and responsive to real-time needs.

5G Networks: The Backbone of a Connected Future

As the demand for faster and more reliable internet continues to grow, 5G technology is poised to take center stage. With download speeds that can reach up to 100 times faster than 4G, 5G will revolutionize everything from mobile connectivity to cloud computing and IoT.

The ultra-low latency and high bandwidth of 5G will unlock new possibilities in sectors like autonomous vehicles, remote surgery, and augmented reality (AR). For example, 5G’s low latency will allow for real-time communication between self-driving cars, improving safety and enabling autonomous transportation on a large scale.

The deployment of 5G networks will create a foundation for next-generation innovations, shaping how we interact with technology in the future.

Sustainability and Green Tech: Technology for a Better Tomorrow

As the world faces mounting environmental challenges, technology is playing a crucial role in promoting sustainability. Green technologies, such as renewable energy sources (solar, wind, hydro), electric vehicles, and energy-efficient buildings, are becoming more mainstream.

AI and IoT are also contributing to sustainability efforts. AI-powered systems are helping companies optimize energy use, reducing waste, and promoting sustainability. IoT devices, meanwhile, are being used to monitor environmental conditions and manage resources more efficiently.

Technology, when used responsibly, can be a force for good, helping to address climate change, reduce carbon footprints, and build a more sustainable future.

Conclusion: Embracing Change

The rapid pace of technological advancement presents both challenges and opportunities. While the potential for innovation is limitless, it’s important to navigate these changes responsibly, ensuring that technology benefits society as a whole.

As we look to the future, it's clear that technology will continue to be a driving force in shaping our lives. From AI to blockchain and IoT, these emerging technologies will not only change the way we work and live but also open doors to new possibilities that we are only beginning to explore.

The future of technology is bright, and it’s up to us to embrace it, harness its power, and use it for the greater good.

fields.title: Technology Hack You Won't Get
fields.author: Arthur Morgan
fields.content:
In today’s fast-paced world, technology continues to reshape our lives in unexpected and astonishing ways. Yet, amidst the sea of productivity apps, AI-driven tools, and smart gadgets, there's always a little-known hack lurking in the shadows — a trick so unique and ingenious that most people won’t even know it exists.

This post is dedicated to uncovering a technology hack that might just blow your mind and leave you wondering, *"How did I not know this before?"

The Hack: Using Your Router as a Digital Butler

 

Wait, what? Yes, you read that right. Your humble Wi-Fi router, the unsung hero of your connected life, can become the backbone of an automated digital assistant system. Here’s how:

Step 1: Leverage Parental Controls for Productivity

Most modern routers come with advanced parental controls. While they’re traditionally used to limit internet access for certain devices or during specific times, you can repurpose them for productivity. For example:

  • Block distractions: Create a profile for your work devices and set restrictions on social media or entertainment websites during working hours.

  • Automate breaks: Schedule brief disconnection periods to remind yourself to step away from the screen and take a breather.

Step 2: Turn on Traffic Monitoring for Insights

Your router logs valuable data about your network usage. By accessing these logs, you can:

  • Identify which devices or apps consume the most bandwidth.

  • Optimize your network by prioritizing critical devices (like work laptops) over non-essential ones (like gaming consoles).

  • Spot unusual activity that might indicate a security breach or malware.

Step 3: Trigger Smart Home Devices

 

Many routers now integrate seamlessly with smart home ecosystems like Alexa or Google Home. Use this capability to:

  • Automate lighting: Link your router to turn on smart lights when you connect your phone to the Wi-Fi after sunset.

  • Smart scheduling: Set routines that kick off when specific devices join or leave the network. For instance, automatically power on your coffee machine when your laptop connects in the morning.

Step 4: Enable Remote Access for Peace of Mind

With secure remote access, your router lets you monitor your home network while you’re away. You can:

  • Ensure your smart security cameras are online.

  • Reboot devices remotely to fix connectivity issues.

  • Grant temporary guest access to friends or family.

Why This Hack Matters

This hack isn’t about downloading the latest app or buying a new gadget. Instead, it’s about unlocking the hidden potential of a device you already own. Your router can become more than just a Wi-Fi provider; it can be the hub of your digital life, streamlining tasks, enhancing productivity, and making your home smarter than ever.

So, the next time you glance at your router, remember: it’s not just a box of blinking lights. With a little creativity and know-how, it can be your secret weapon for better living.
